quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  24,37,"<span class=""h"">are men</span>whom neither bargain nor sale distracts from Allah’s remembrance or from establishing the prayers or from bringing{1}the purifying charity{2}, fearing a day when hearts and sight<i class=""s"">(s) </i>are overturned,",footnotes:1:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|2:The Arabic word used is zakāt, which denotes purification and growth.
  24,38,"<i class=""s"">(in the hope) </i>that Allah may repay them according to the best of what they have done and increase them from His grace. For Allah provides for whomever He wills without measure."
  24,39,"But those who have denied—their deeds are like a mirage in a desert: the thirsty one thinks it is water until when he has reached it he finds it to be nothing, but there he finds Allah, Who settles his account in full. For Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  24,40,"Or<i class=""s"">(they are) </i>like darkness<i class=""s"">(es) </i>{1}in an abysmal sea, covered by waves, above which are waves, above which are <span class=""h"">clouds—darkness</span><i class=""s"">(es) </i><sup foot_note=""80668"" class=""qiraat"">2</sup>, one upon the other. If one holds out his hand, he can hardly see it. For whomever Allah has not granted a light has no light.",footnotes:1:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (es) in English for grammatical reasons.
  24,41,"Have you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>not seen how Allah is highly exalted by whoever is in the heavens and the earth and by the birds outstretching their wings, each having come to know its<i class=""s"">(way of) </i>prayer and exaltation? And Allah is All-Knowing of what they do."
  24,42,"For to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, and to Allah is the destiny."
  24,43,"Have you not seen how Allah propels clouds, then brings them together, then piles them up in heaps so you see rainfall coming out of its midst? And He <span class=""h"">sends down<sup foot_note=""80669"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>from the sky—from mountains in it— some hail, striking with it whomever He wills and diverting it from whomever He wills? The flash of its lightening almost does away with the sight<i class=""s"">(s) </i>."
